Germany Daybook: Deutsche Bank Profit Rises on Consumer Banking

-- B y   N i c h o l a s   C o m f o r t
-- 
2011-04-28T05:51:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/germany-daybook-deutsche-bank-profit-rises-on-consumer-banking.html
Deutsche Bank AG (DBK) , Germany’s biggest
bank, reported a 17 percent increase in first-quarter profit,
exceeding analyst estimates on record earnings at the consumer-
banking and asset management units.  Net income climbed to 2.1 billion euros ($3.1 billion), the
second-best quarterly result ever, from 1.8 billion euros in the
year-earlier period, the Frankfurt-based bank said in a
statement today. Earnings surpassed the 1.8 billion-euro average
estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.  EQUITIES:
*SAP (SAP GR) reported a 4.1% increase in first-quarter profit,
missing analysts’ estimates, and confirmed its full-year
outlook.
*Bayer (SAP GR) raised its forecast for sales and earnings this
year, mainly because of an improvement at its crop-chemical
business. The company commented in an e-mailed statement.
* Hugo Boss  (BOS3 GR) reported 1q net income of EU81.9M, beating
the average estimate of EU73.2M in a Bloomberg survey of six
analysts.
*Siemens (SIE@GR) said it will close a plant that employs 200
workers near Zurich and invest 170 million Swiss francs to build
an international headquarters for its Building Technologies
Division and a factory in Zug.
*Salzgitter (SZG@GR) wants to reduce dependence on the steel
business by developing its technology unit, Handelsblatt
reported, citing an interview with CEO Heinz Joerg Fuhrmann.
*Munich Re (MUV2@GR) said insurers and reinsurers face
incalculable risks from protecting clients against the costs of
supplier disruption after the earthquake in  Japan  led to factory
stoppages,  Sueddeutsche Zeitung  reported.  ECONOMY:
*Belgium will probably back Bank of Italy Governor  Mario Draghi 
to succeed  Jean-Claude Trichet  as president of the  European
Central Bank , said Dominique Dehaene, a spokesman for caretaker
Prime Minister Yves Leterme.
*Spanish Finance Minister Elena Salgado said Draghi is an
“excellent” candidate to succeed Trichet, although the period
for presenting candidates hasn’t opened yet.
*Klaus Regling, the head of the European Financial Stability
Facility, said investor demand for bonds sold to provide aid to
debt-strapped governments shows that concerns about the euro’s
future have dissipated.
*Spain’s regions and central government agreed on a budget
deficit target for the regions of 1 percent of gross domestic
product for 2014, the  finance ministry  said in a statement.
*Maria Fekter, Austria’s finance minister, said she is “not a
friend” of a Greek debt restructuring because this would take
pressure off the Greek government to tackle its debt problems.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*German March import prices at 8 a.m.
* Germany ’s energy security commission will hold a session
starting at 9 a.m. to be broadcast via the government’s website.
*German April unemployment rate at 9:55 a.m.
*ECB’s Yves Mersch to speak in Luxembourg  MARKETS:
*The DAX Index rose 0.7% to 7,404.95
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index gained 0.3% to 282.12
*MSCI Asia-Pacific Index rose 1.3% to 139.55 as of 7:45 a.m. in
Frankfurt.
 *German 10-year bond yield at 3.33%
